#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:3
msgid "NumPy 1.7.0 Release Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:5
msgid ""
"This release includes several new features as well as numerous bug fixes and "
"refactorings. It supports Python 2.4 - 2.7 and 3.1 - 3.3 and is the last "
"release that supports Python 2.4 - 2.5."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:10
msgid "Highlights"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:12
msgid ""
"``where=`` parameter to ufuncs (allows the use of boolean arrays to choose "
"where a computation should be done)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:14
msgid ""
"``vectorize`` improvements (added 'excluded' and 'cache' keyword, general "
"cleanup and bug fixes)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:16
msgid "``numpy.random.choice`` (random sample generating function)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:20
msgid "Compatibility notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:22
msgid ""
"In a future version of numpy, the functions np.diag, np.diagonal, and the "
"diagonal method of ndarrays will return a view onto the original array, "
"instead of producing a copy as they do now. This makes a difference if you "
"write to the array returned by any of these functions. To facilitate this "
"transition, numpy 1.7 produces a FutureWarning if it detects that you may be "
"attempting to write to such an array. See the documentation for np.diagonal "
"for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:30
msgid ""
"Similar to np.diagonal above, in a future version of numpy, indexing a "
"record array by a list of field names will return a view onto the original "
"array, instead of producing a copy as they do now. As with np.diagonal, "
"numpy 1.7 produces a FutureWarning if it detects that you may be attempting "
"to write to such an array. See the documentation for array indexing for "
"details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:37
msgid ""
"In a future version of numpy, the default casting rule for UFunc out= "
"parameters will be changed from 'unsafe' to 'same_kind'. (This also applies "
"to in-place operations like a += b, which is equivalent to np.add(a, b, "
"out=a).) Most usages which violate the 'same_kind' rule are likely bugs, so "
"this change may expose previously undetected errors in projects that depend "
"on NumPy. In this version of numpy, such usages will continue to succeed, "
"but will raise a DeprecationWarning."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:45
msgid ""
"Full-array boolean indexing has been optimized to use a different, optimized "
"code path.   This code path should produce the same results, but any "
"feedback about changes to your code would be appreciated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:49
msgid ""
"Attempting to write to a read-only array (one with ``arr.flags.writeable`` "
"set to ``False``) used to raise either a RuntimeError, ValueError, or "
"TypeError inconsistently, depending on which code path was taken. It now "
"consistently raises a ValueError."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:54
msgid ""
"The <ufunc>.reduce functions evaluate some reductions in a different order "
"than in previous versions of NumPy, generally providing higher performance. "
"Because of the nature of floating-point arithmetic, this may subtly change "
"some results, just as linking NumPy to a different BLAS implementations such "
"as MKL can."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:60
msgid ""
"If upgrading from 1.5, then generally in 1.6 and 1.7 there have been "
"substantial code added and some code paths altered, particularly in the "
"areas of type resolution and buffered iteration over universal functions. "
"This might have an impact on your code particularly if you relied on "
"accidental behavior in the past."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:67
msgid "New features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:70
msgid "Reduction UFuncs Generalize axis= Parameter"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:72
msgid ""
"Any ufunc.reduce function call, as well as other reductions like sum, prod, "
"any, all, max and min support the ability to choose a subset of the axes to "
"reduce over. Previously, one could say axis=None to mean all the axes or "
"axis=# to pick a single axis.  Now, one can also say axis=(#,#) to pick a "
"list of axes for reduction."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:79
msgid "Reduction UFuncs New keepdims= Parameter"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:81
msgid ""
"There is a new keepdims= parameter, which if set to True, doesn't throw away "
"the reduction axes but instead sets them to have size one.  When this option "
"is set, the reduction result will broadcast correctly to the original "
"operand which was reduced."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:87
msgid "Datetime support"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:89
msgid ""
"The datetime API is *experimental* in 1.7.0, and may undergo changes in "
"future versions of NumPy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:92
msgid ""
"There have been a lot of fixes and enhancements to datetime64 compared to "
"NumPy 1.6:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:95
msgid ""
"the parser is quite strict about only accepting ISO 8601 dates, with a few "
"convenience extensions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:97
msgid "converts between units correctly"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:98
msgid "datetime arithmetic works correctly"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:99
msgid ""
"business day functionality (allows the datetime to be used in contexts where "
"only certain days of the week are valid)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:102
msgid ""
"The notes in `doc/source/reference/arrays.datetime.rst <https://github.com/"
"numpy/numpy/blob/maintenance/1.7.x/doc/source/reference/arrays.datetime."
"rst>`_ (also available in the online docs at `arrays.datetime.html <https://"
"docs.scipy.org/doc/numpy/reference/arrays.datetime.html>`_) should be "
"consulted for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:108
msgid "Custom formatter for printing arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:110
msgid ""
"See the new ``formatter`` parameter of the ``numpy.set_printoptions`` "
"function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:114
msgid "New function numpy.random.choice"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:116
msgid ""
"A generic sampling function has been added which will generate samples from "
"a given array-like. The samples can be with or without replacement, and with "
"uniform or given non-uniform probabilities."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:121
msgid "New function isclose"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:123
msgid ""
"Returns a boolean array where two arrays are element-wise equal within a "
"tolerance. Both relative and absolute tolerance can be specified."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:127
msgid "Preliminary multi-dimensional support in the polynomial package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:129
msgid ""
"Axis keywords have been added to the integration and differentiation "
"functions and a tensor keyword was added to the evaluation functions. These "
"additions allow multi-dimensional coefficient arrays to be used in those "
"functions. New functions for evaluating 2-D and 3-D coefficient arrays on "
"grids or sets of points were added together with 2-D and 3-D pseudo-"
"Vandermonde matrices that can be used for fitting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:138
msgid "Ability to pad rank-n arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:140
msgid ""
"A pad module containing functions for padding n-dimensional arrays has been "
"added. The various private padding functions are exposed as options to a "
"public 'pad' function.  Example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:144
msgid "pad(a, 5, mode='mean')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:146
msgid ""
"Current modes are ``constant``, ``edge``, ``linear_ramp``, ``maximum``, "
"``mean``, ``median``, ``minimum``, ``reflect``, ``symmetric``, ``wrap``, and "
"``<function>``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:152
msgid "New argument to searchsorted"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:154
msgid ""
"The function searchsorted now accepts a 'sorter' argument that is a "
"permutation array that sorts the array to search."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:158
msgid "Build system"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:160
msgid "Added experimental support for the AArch64 architecture."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:163
msgid "C API"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:165
msgid ""
"New function ``PyArray_FailUnlessWriteable`` provides a consistent interface "
"for checking array writeability -- any C code which works with arrays whose "
"WRITEABLE flag is not known to be True a priori, should make sure to call "
"this function before writing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:170
msgid "NumPy C Style Guide added (``doc/C_STYLE_GUIDE.rst``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:173
msgid "Changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:176 ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:259
msgid "General"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:178
msgid ""
"The function np.concatenate tries to match the layout of its input arrays. "
"Previously, the layout did not follow any particular reason, and depended in "
"an undesirable way on the particular axis chosen for concatenation. A bug "
"was also fixed which silently allowed out of bounds axis arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:183
msgid ""
"The ufuncs logical_or, logical_and, and logical_not now follow Python's "
"behavior with object arrays, instead of trying to call methods on the "
"objects. For example the expression (3 and 'test') produces the string "
"'test', and now np.logical_and(np.array(3, 'O'), np.array('test', 'O')) "
"produces 'test' as well."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:189
msgid ""
"The ``.base`` attribute on ndarrays, which is used on views to ensure that "
"the underlying array owning the memory is not deallocated prematurely, now "
"collapses out references when you have a view-of-a-view. For example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:193
msgid ""
"a = np.arange(10)\n"
"b = a[1:]\n"
"c = b[1:]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:197
msgid ""
"In numpy 1.6, ``c.base`` is ``b``, and ``c.base.base`` is ``a``. In numpy "
"1.7, ``c.base`` is ``a``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:200
msgid ""
"To increase backwards compatibility for software which relies on the old "
"behaviour of ``.base``, we only 'skip over' objects which have exactly the "
"same type as the newly created view. This makes a difference if you use "
"``ndarray`` subclasses. For example, if we have a mix of ``ndarray`` and "
"``matrix`` objects which are all views on the same original ``ndarray``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:206
msgid ""
"a = np.arange(10)\n"
"b = np.asmatrix(a)\n"
"c = b[0, 1:]\n"
"d = c[0, 1:]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:211
msgid ""
"then ``d.base`` will be ``b``. This is because ``d`` is a ``matrix`` object, "
"and so the collapsing process only continues so long as it encounters other "
"``matrix`` objects. It considers ``c``, ``b``, and ``a`` in that order, and "
"``b`` is the last entry in that list which is a ``matrix`` object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:217
msgid "Casting Rules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:219
msgid ""
"Casting rules have undergone some changes in corner cases, due to the NA-"
"related work. In particular for combinations of scalar+scalar:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:222
msgid ""
"the `longlong` type (`q`) now stays `longlong` for operations with any other "
"number (`? b h i l q p B H I`), previously it was cast as `int_` (`l`). The "
"`ulonglong` type (`Q`) now stays as `ulonglong` instead of `uint` (`L`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:226
msgid ""
"the `timedelta64` type (`m`) can now be mixed with any integer type (`b h i "
"l q p B H I L Q P`), previously it raised `TypeError`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:229
msgid ""
"For array + scalar, the above rules just broadcast except the case when the "
"array and scalars are unsigned/signed integers, then the result gets "
"converted to the array type (of possibly larger size) as illustrated by the "
"following examples::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:234
msgid ""
">>> (np.zeros((2,), dtype=np.uint8) + np.int16(257)).dtype\n"
"dtype('uint16')\n"
">>> (np.zeros((2,), dtype=np.int8) + np.uint16(257)).dtype\n"
"dtype('int16')\n"
">>> (np.zeros((2,), dtype=np.int16) + np.uint32(2**17)).dtype\n"
"dtype('int32')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:241
msgid ""
"Whether the size gets increased depends on the size of the scalar, for "
"example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:244
msgid ""
">>> (np.zeros((2,), dtype=np.uint8) + np.int16(255)).dtype\n"
"dtype('uint8')\n"
">>> (np.zeros((2,), dtype=np.uint8) + np.int16(256)).dtype\n"
"dtype('uint16')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:249
msgid ""
"Also a ``complex128`` scalar + ``float32`` array is cast to ``complex64``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:251
msgid ""
"In NumPy 1.7 the `datetime64` type (`M`) must be constructed by explicitly "
"specifying the type as the second argument (e.g. ``np.datetime64(2000, "
"'Y')``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:256
msgid "Deprecations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:261
msgid ""
"Specifying a custom string formatter with a `_format` array attribute is "
"deprecated. The new ``formatter`` keyword in ``numpy.set_printoptions`` or "
"``numpy.array2string`` can be used instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:265
msgid "The deprecated imports in the polynomial package have been removed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:267
msgid ""
"``concatenate`` now raises DepractionWarning for 1D arrays if ``axis != 0``. "
"Versions of numpy < 1.7.0 ignored axis argument value for 1D arrays. We "
"allow this for now, but in due course we will raise an error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:272
msgid "C-API"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:274
msgid ""
"Direct access to the fields of PyArrayObject* has been deprecated. Direct "
"access has been recommended against for many releases. Expect similar "
"deprecations for PyArray_Descr* and other core objects in the future as "
"preparation for NumPy 2.0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:279
msgid ""
"The macros in old_defines.h are deprecated and will be removed in the next "
"major release (>= 2.0). The sed script tools/replace_old_macros.sed can be "
"used to replace these macros with the newer versions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:283
msgid ""
"You can test your code against the deprecated C API by adding a line "
"composed of ``#define NPY_NO_DEPRECATED_API`` and the target version number, "
"such as ``NPY_1_7_API_VERSION``, before including any NumPy headers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.7.0-notes.rst:287
msgid ""
"The ``NPY_CHAR`` member of the ``NPY_TYPES`` enum is deprecated and will be "
"removed in NumPy 1.8. See the discussion at `gh-2801 <https://github.com/"
"numpy/numpy/issues/2801>`_ for more details."
msgstr ""
